{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"651c1975-e9d2-411e-9ce2-4f4fdbf4836d","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or ephemeral debug container: `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0`\n- For low-overhead production use, consider `--profile cpu-sampling` (default 10ms interval) — it's safe for prod.\n- To copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20c87b68-0d94-477a-b912-ab4d4a44b228","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"A0FB:5645A:104D56A:132B3AE:6A013133"},"id":"c9090bfb-457a-4b96-b7b2-592c5029631c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:30:36.368Z","parentId":"ed30a951-3872-49c8-900c-1d979a69e788"}
